<br>
New Delhi - May 23, 2002<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spacedaily.com/news/nuclear-india-pakistan-02r1.html">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
India Thursday rejected calls to engage Pakistan in talks over Kashmir, as Islamabad announced the recall of troops on foreign duty and Britain warned confrontation between the bitter rivals could escalate into nuclear war. Fears of all-out warfare, meanwhile, wiped another 1.9 percent off the Bombay Stock Exchange, while Pakistan's main bourse remained shut Thursday to avert further heavy losses posted over the past four days.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/24/02 3:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=303.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: No Talks, Says India, Amid Warnings Of Nuke War</span><hr size=1> There have been a great many of these crises recently, so I'm afraid that the public, at least in the west, is going glassy eyed over them. The pattern is alarming, however. Each war scare seems to move closer to the brink than the last, and the underlying causes of conflict appear to be completely intractable. India is fed up with Islamic terrorism, it blames Pakistan, and it is spoiling for a fight. <br>
My personal opinion is that war is almost inevitable, and it will catch the western masses by surprise in spite of (or perhaps because of) the many warnings. I don't know whether it will turn nuclear, but events could take on a life of their own in defiance of any rational consideration. A lot depends on the extent to which the Pakistani leadership has been infected by the suicide jihadi mentality currently sweeping the Muslim world. Musharraf is rational, but we cannot be sure how secure he will be under the stress of yet another desperate crisis. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/25/02 3:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=303.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: No Talks, Says India, Amid Warnings Of Nuke War</span><hr size=1> Warblogger <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.palit.com/tkl.asp">Suman Palit</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> does not believe that <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.palit.com/2002_05_19_tkl_archive.asp#85106363">Musharraf is as rational </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->as westerners, especially Americans, commonly give him credit for.<br>
Palit has quite a bit of analysis of Musharraf's statements and behavior and some very disturbing links about Pakistani nuclear strategy, including a contention that the Paks favor a first strike. Given their enormous disadvantage in conventional forces, and the suicide jihadi hysteria, this is at least plausible.<br>
<br>
On a different front, CBS news said today that &quot;scientists&quot; had calculated that even a very limited nuclear exchange between India and Pakistan would kill at least 3 million people. This is very easy to believe, but the scientists were not named and there was no indication of just what was meant by &quot;very limited exchange.&quot; <br>
My own guess is that we are looking at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/nuke/guide/pakistan/index.html">Pakistan</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> throwing all their nukes (up to 25, but more likely 12-15) at India if it comes to that. The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/nuke/guide/india/index.html">Indians</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (who almost certainly have close to 100 warheads and possibly more) would retaliate at a greater than 1 to 1 ratio, with this being mitigated somewhat by the need to hold some back to deter the Chinese. We are still looking at upwards of 50 nuclear explosions in one of the most densely populated areas of the world. Fatalities will easily be in the tens of millions, with millions more dying from residual effects and the general disruption of a population that is on the thin edge of survival at the best of times.<br>
Public reaction in the West will almost certainly include panic and hysteria at a level never seen before. I hope that FEMA is ready for this, but I am not optimistic. <br>
I have already seen messages asking how to get potassium iodide tablets and even wondering if these are already on hand at the nation's schools.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/25/02 5:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=303.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: No Talks, Says India, Amid Warnings Of Nuke War</span><hr size=1> If Pakistan launches a nuke attack against India with the wind at<br>
their back, then if India stikes pakistan, they will end up with <br>
radioactive fallout on their own population! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1327<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/29/02 1:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=303.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.gothicbarbie.net/images/electric.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: No Talks, Says India, Amid Warnings Of Nuke War</span><hr size=1> India and Pakistan could easily trigger a World War. Smaller events have. The entire global scene will change over night. Once the first nuke is dropped both sides will use up everything they have in tit for tat reprisals. Both countries will be hit hard but the war wont be over. The military will not be held back. The dogs of war will be unleashed and they will savage one another until the rest of the World steps in and pulls them apart.........or joins in.<br>
Battles over territory frequently spill out and over into other nations. Sides will be taken. Poland, Korea and Vietnam were small scales international affairs. This will be bigger. <br>
<br>
Perhaps it will come to naught this time as it has many times in the past. Perhaps not. One thing for certain is that some day the line will be crossed. The nuclear genie cannot be rebottled. What a shame it would be if we never fully recognised and utilised the peaceful applications of nuclear power. That our futile attempts to ban nuclear technology destroyed the one possible hope of salvation. Nuclear technology could be our saviour against nuclear technology. Ignoring research hasn't deterred this or previous nuclear threats and it wont work in the future ever. The sooner we reverse our policy the better our chance of survival as an advanced civilisation. <p>
